<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>EvalScript Error Fix</h1>
        <p class="subtitle">Panel opens but all tests fail? Fix it in 30 seconds.</p>

        <div class="error-box">
            <div class="error-title">⚠️ The Problem</div>
            <div class="error-text">
                All JSX tests are failing with <strong>"EvalScript error"</strong> - this means Premiere Pro
                is blocking the extension from running ExtendScript code. This is a security feature.
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="fix-box">
            <div class="fix-title">✅ The Fix (30 seconds)</div>

            <ol class="steps">
                <li>
                    <strong>Copy this command:</strong>
                    <div class="command-box" id="command">
                        <button class="copy-btn" onclick="copyCommand()">Copy</button>
defaults write com.adobe.CSXS.9 PlayerDebugMode 1; defaults write com.adobe.CSXS.10 PlayerDebugMode 1; defaults write com.adobe.CSXS.11 PlayerDebugMode 1; defaults write com.adobe.CSXS.12 PlayerDebugMode 1; defaults write com.adobe.CSXS.13 PlayerDebugMode 1; echo "✅ Debug mode enabled!"
                    </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Open Terminal</strong> (press Cmd+Space, type "terminal", hit Enter)
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Paste the command</strong> and press Enter
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>QUIT Premiere Pro</strong> completely (Cmd+Q, not just close window)
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Restart Premiere Pro</strong>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Click the debug button</strong> (magnifying glass) and run diagnostics again
                </li>
            </ol>

            <div class="success">
                ✅ All 6 tests should now pass!
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="warning">
            <strong>What did that command do?</strong><br>
            It enabled CEP debug mode for all Adobe CEP versions (9-13). This tells Premiere Pro
            to allow unsigned extensions like SPLICE to run ExtendScript code. This is safe and
            commonly used by developers.
        </div>

        <div class="warning">
            <strong>Still not working?</strong><br>
            1. Make sure you COMPLETELY quit Premiere Pro (Cmd+Q)<br>
            2. Clear CEP cache: <code>rm -rf ~/Library/Caches/Adobe/CEP</code><br>
            3. Restart Premiere Pro<br>
            4. Open Chrome and go to <code>http://localhost:8092</code><br>
            5. Click "SPLICE" to see debug logs
        </div>

        <div style="text-align: center; margin-top: 40px; color: #6b7280; font-size: 14px;">
            SPLICE v6.0.5 | Updated: January 12, 2026
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        function copyCommand() {
            const command = document.getElementById('command').textContent.replace('Copy', '').trim();
            navigator.clipboard.writeText(command).then(() => {
                const btn = document.querySelector('.copy-btn');
                const originalText = btn.textContent;
                btn.textContent = '✓ Copied!';
                btn.style.background = '#10b981';
                setTimeout(() => {
                    btn.textContent = originalText;
                    btn.style.background = '#00D4FF';
                }, 2000);
            });
        }
    </script>
